GitHub Copilot: Great question. Let me lay out the real implications for **live updates vs periodic refresh**, especially considering you'll be maintaining this via AI:

## Live Updates Architecture

**What it means technically:**
- Backend establishes WebSocket connection to the frontend (always open)
- Backend actively listens to Google Photos and Calendar APIs for changes
- When something new arrives, it pushes to the display in real-time

**Implications:**
- ✅ **User experience**: Photos appear instantly, calendar pops up when events are added
- ✅ **Feels "alive"**: More polished, responsive
- ❌ **Power**: Raspberry Pi is constantly listening and processing (higher CPU/battery if battery-backed)
- ❌ **Complexity**: More moving parts—WebSockets, real-time listeners, connection recovery logic
- ❌ **Maintenance burden**: More edge cases (network drops, API rate limits, connection timeouts)—AI can help, but more to debug
- ❌ **Google/Apple API limits**: Google Photos doesn't have true push notifications; you'd be polling frequently anyway, so you still get some delays

## Periodic Refresh (e.g., every 15 min)

**What it means:**
- Backend wakes up every 15 minutes, fetches new photos/calendar, sends to frontend
- Frontend displays whatever arrived in that batch

**Implications:**
- ✅ **Simplicity**: Timer + fetch + update. Much easier to reason about and maintain
- ✅ **Power**: Raspberry Pi mostly sleeping, wakes only when needed
- ✅ **Reliability**: No complex connection state to manage
- ✅ **API friendly**: Respects rate limits, predictable load on Google/Apple
- ❌ **Slight lag**: New photos might wait 15 mins to appear
- ❌ **Less "alive"**: Feels more like a static display that updates occasionally

## The Reality Check

Here's the thing: **Google Photos doesn't have real-time push APIs.** You'll be polling either way. So "live updates" really means "poll every 30-60 seconds" vs "poll every 15 minutes." The difference isn't dramatic from a UX perspective.

## My Recommendation for Your Situation

Given:
- You're maintaining via AI (not touching code)
- You want this stable behind your kitchen display
- Low power consumption matters
- Shareability matters (others copying your setup)

**I'd lean toward periodic refresh (15-30 min).** Here's why:
- **AI maintenance is easier**: Fewer edge cases, simpler debugging
- **More reliable**: Less state to manage
- **Power efficient**: Matters on Raspberry Pi long-term
- **Easier for others to replicate**: No complex WebSocket infrastructure
- **Good enough UX**: 15-min delay on a kitchen display is genuinely fine for photos/calendar

The "live feel" you get from periodic refresh is actually pretty good—users won't notice a 15-min delay on a passive display.

**Does that reasoning resonate, or does the real-time aspect matter for your use case?** (e.g., "I want calendar alerts to pop immediately")

