Compacted conversationNo, tablets typically do not have dedicated HDMI ports. Most modern tablets (like Samsung Galaxy Tab, Apple iPad, or Android tablets) use USB-C ports for video output. To connect to HDMI, you need a USB-C to HDMI adapter or cable, which converts the USB-C signal (often using DisplayPort Alt Mode) to HDMI. This is standard for tablets and doesn't involve a separate "HDMI port" - the USB-C port handles the video output.

Yes, full-screen capability is feasible for the interactive web app mode. In this setup, the tablet's browser connects to the Raspberry Pi's web server over WiFi, and the display renders directly on the tablet's screen. Browsers on tablets (Safari on iPad, Chrome on Android tablets) support full-screen mode via JavaScript APIs like `requestFullscreen()`. You can implement this in your React app to make the interface fill the entire tablet screen, hiding browser UI elements for a kiosk-like experience. This works well for touch interaction and doesn't require HDMI.

